        <p>
            This section covers the fundamentals of writing, evaluating, and applying numerical expressions. 
        </p>
        <p>Suppose your kitchen sink has sprung a leak. You hire a plumber who charges a flat $50 service fee plus $75 per hour of labor. If the plumber works for 3 hours, how much will you owe?
    </p>
        
    <p>To calculate the total cost, you could write the following mathematical expression:
        <men xml:id="plumber-cost-numerical-expression">50 + 75 \cdot 3</men>
        Evaluating this expression gives the total cost of $275.
    </p>

    <p>The above expression <xref ref="plumber-cost-numerical-expression"/> is an example of a <term>numerical expression</term>.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-numerical-expression">
        <statement>
            <p>A <term>numerical expression</term> is an expression formed only from numbers and the basic operations of arithmetic. Numerical expressions may also contain grouping symbols like: <m>(...), [...], \{...\}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
     <example xml:id="example-numerical-expressions">
       <p>The following are additional examples of numerical expressions:
        <md>
            <mrow>&amp; 5 \cdot 3 - 2</mrow>
            <mrow>&amp; 10 + 7 \cdot 2</mrow>
            <mrow>&amp; (8-3)^2 + 6 \div 3</mrow>
            <mrow>&amp; 2 \cdot 3 + 4 \cdot 5 - 6 \div 2</mrow>
        </md>
        </p>
    </example>
    <p>In this section, we will learn how to write numerical expressions from their verbal descriptions, evaluate them using the order of operations, and apply them to solve real-world problems.
    </p>

    </introduction>

    <!-- Subsection for "Learn Writing Numerical Expressions" -->
    <subsection xml:id="subsection-writing-numerical-expressions">
        <title><em>Learn</em>: Writing Numerical Expressions</title>
        
        <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-translate-verbal-expression-without-grouping">
        <title>Translate a Verbal Expression without Grouping Symbols</title>
            
        <p>The verbal expression "twelve divided by four plus two" can be translated into the numerical expression:
            <me>12 \div 4 + 2</me>
        </p>
        <p>In general, we translate simple verbal expressions into numerical expressions as follows:</p>
        <p><ul>
            <li>
                <p> "five plus three" <m>\rightarrow 5 + 3 </m> (Addition)</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p> "five minus three" <m>\rightarrow 5 - 3 </m> (Subtraction)</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p> "five times three" <m>\rightarrow 5 \cdot 3 </m> (Multiplication)</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p> "five divided by three" <m>\rightarrow 5 \div 3 </m> or <m>\frac{5}{3} </m> (Division)</p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
        <exercise xml:id="exercise-translate-verbal-expression-without-grouping">
            <title>Translate a Verbal Expression</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Translate the verbal expression "eight minus three times two" into a numerical expression.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>8 - 3 \cdot 2</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </subsubsection>

<subsubsection xml:id="subsec-translate-verbal-expression-with-grouping">
    <title>Translate a Verbal Expression with Grouping Symbols</title>
        <p>
            Some verbal expressions contain special phrases that refer to the <em>result</em> of a basic arithmetic operations.
            Such expressions require the use of grouping symbols to properly translate them into numerical expressions.
        </p>
        <p>For example, the verbal expression "<em>the sum of five and three</em> times two" is translated into the numerical expression:
            <men xml:id="an-expression-with-grouping-symbols">(5 + 3) \cdot 2</men>
        </p>
        <p>Note in <xref ref="an-expression-with-grouping-symbols"/> above how we have enclosed the addition operation in parentheses: "the sum of five and three" becomes <m>(5 + 3)</m>.
            This is necessary, because when we speak of the "sum" of two numbers, we want to compute with the <em>output</em> of that operation rather than any of its internal parts.
        </p>
            <p> 
            In general, we translate verbal expressions that require grouping symbols as follows:
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        "the sum of" refers to the result of addition <m>(\_\_+\_\_)</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        "the difference of" refers to the result of subtraction <m>(\_\_-\_\_)</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        "the product of" refers to the result of multiplication <m>(\_\_\cdot\_\_)</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        "the quotient of" refers to the result of division <m>(\frac{\;\;\;}{\;\;\;})</m>   
                    </p>
                </li>
            
            </ul>
           </p>
            
        <example xml:id="example-translate-verbal-expression-with-grouping">
            <title>Translate a Verbal Expression with Grouping Symbols</title>
            <statement>
    
            <p>
                <!-- Your content for this example goes here. -->
                Write a numerical expression for each of the following verbal expressions:
                
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            "two times the difference of six and four".
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            "twelve divided by the sum of four and two".
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            "the sum of eight and seven divided by the difference of four and one".
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            "the difference of nine and five times the sum of three and two".
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>2 \cdot (6 - 4)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>12 \div (4 + 2)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>(8 + 7) \div (4 - 1)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>(9 - 5) \cdot (3 + 2)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>   
            
        </example>

</subsubsection>
</subsection>

    <!-- Subsection for "Learn Evaluating Numerical Expressions" -->
    <subsection xml:id="subsection-evaluating-numerical-expressions">
        <title><em>Learn</em>: Evaluating Numerical Expressions</title>
        
    <p>
         <!-- Your content for this subsection goes here. -->
        We have learned how to write numerical expressions from verbal descriptions. But what do such expressions actually mean?
    </p>
          
    <p>Recall the plumbing problem from above. Suppose you were to hand your friend a slip of paper with just the above expression <xref ref="plumber-cost-numerical-expression"/> written on it.
        Without knowing anything about how you were using this expression, your friend should still be able to correctly interpret and evaluate it to get its value of 275.
    </p>    
    <p>That is the power of mathematical language: it allows us to communicate ideas <em>precisely</em> and <em>unambiguously</em>.
        Like all mathematical language, numerical expressions are powerful because they communicate a precise meaning independent from any particular problem they model.
    </p>  
    <p>For numerical expressions, the <term>order of operations</term> tells us the proper sequence for combining the numbers in the expression using the given operations.
        In this way, we can <term>evaluate</term> every numerical expression to a single numerical value. 
    </p> 
    
    <definition xml:id="def-order-of-operations">
        <statement>
            <p>
                The <term>order of operations</term> gives the proper order to evaluate any numerical expression:
                <ol>
                    <li>First, evaluate inside parentheses (...) and other grouping symbols.</li>
                    <li>Next, evaluate exponents (powers and roots or radicals).</li>
                    <li>Then, perform multiplication and division from left to right.</li>
                    <li>Finally, perform addition and subtraction from left to right.</li>
                </ol>
                Note: Multiplication does not always come before Division, and Addition does not always come before Subtraction. They are performed from left to right as they appear in the expression.
                 </p>
                <p> The above order of operations can be remembered using the acronym <em>PEMDAS</em>, which stands for Parentheses, Exponents, Multiplication/Division, Addition/Subtraction.
                </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <example xml:id="example-evaluate-numerical-expressions">
        <title>Evaluate numerical expressions using the order of operations</title>
        <statement>
        <p>Use the order of operations to evaluate the numerical expressions from <xref ref="example-numerical-expressions"/>
            <md>
            <mrow>&amp; 5 /cdot 3 - 2 = \_\_\_</mrow>
            <mrow>&amp; 10 + 7 \cdot 2 = \_\_\_</mrow>
            <mrow>&amp; (8-3)^2 + 6 \div 3 = \_\_\_</mrow>
            <mrow>&amp; 2 \cdot 3 + 4 \cdot 5 - 6 \div 2 = \_\_\_</mrow>
            </md> 
        </p>
        </statement>
    <answer>
        <p>
            <md>
            <mrow>&amp; 5 \cdot 3 - 2 = 13</mrow>
            <mrow>&amp; 10 + 7 \cdot 2 = 24</mrow>
            <mrow>&amp; (8-3)^2 + 6 \div 3 = 27 </mrow>
            <mrow>&amp; 2 \cdot 3 + 4 \cdot 5 - 6 \div 2 = 23</mrow>
            </md> 
        </p>
    </answer>
    </example>

     <p>
        <!-- Your content for this example goes here. -->
        For example, when evaluating the expression <me>5 + 3^2 \cdot (4-1)</me> we follow the order of operations as shown below: 
            <md>
                <mrow> \amp 5 + 3^2 \cdot (4-1) =</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp 5 + 3^2 \cdot 3 =</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp 5 + 9 \cdot 3 =</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp 5 + 27 =</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp 32</mrow>
            </md>  
        First, we evaluate inside the parentheses. Next, we compute the exponent. Then, we multiply. Finally, we add and get the expression's value of <m>32</m>.
        </p>

        <example xml:id="example-evaluate-numerical-expression">
            <title>Evaluate a Numerical Expression</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                Evaluate the expression <m>2^2 - 10 \div 5</m>. 
                 </p>
            </statement>
           
            <answer>
                <p>
                  We first evaluate the exponent <m>2^2 = 4</m>, then perform the division <m>10 \div 5 = 2</m>, and finally subtract these two results to get <m>4 - 2 = 2</m>.  
                </p>
            </answer>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="example-evaluate-numerical-expression-with-grouping">
            <title>Evaluate a Numerical Expression with Grouping Symbols</title>
            <statement>
            <p>
                <!-- Your content for this example goes here. -->
                Evaluate the expression <m>(2 + 3) \cdot (4 - 1)</m>. 
            </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    We first evaluate the two expressions in parentheses to get <m>5</m> and <m>3</m>, respectively, and then multiply these results to get <m>15</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </example>
        
        <example xml:id="exanmple-write-and-evaluate-numerical-expression">
            <title>Write and Evaluate a Numerical Expression</title>
            <statement>
            <p>
                Translate and evaluate the verbal expression "the difference of 10 and 4 multiplied by 2."
            </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>We write this expression as <m>(10 - 4) \cdot 2</m> and evaluate it to get <m>6 \cdot 2 = 12</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>   
            </example>

        <exercise xml:id="exercise-evaluate-numerical-expressions">
            <title>Evaluate Numerical Expressions</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Evaluate the following numerical expressions using the order of operations:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>&amp; 8 + 2^3 - 4 \div 2</mrow>
                        <mrow>&amp; (6 + 2) \cdot 3 - 5</mrow>
                        <mrow>&amp; 12 \div (3 + 1) + 2^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    The results are:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>&amp; 8 + 8 - 2 = 14</mrow>
                        <mrow>&amp; 8 \cdot 3 - 5 = 19</mrow>
                        <mrow>&amp; 12 \div 4 + 4 = 7</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        
    </subsection>

    <!-- Subsection for "Learn Plan for Problem Solving" -->
    <subsection xml:id="subsection-plan-for-problem-solving">
        <title><em>Learn</em>: Plan for Problem Solving</title>

        <p>
            <!-- Your content for this subsection goes here. -->
            To solve real-world problems, we often need to write numerical expressions that model the situation.
            The key steps are:
            <ol>
                <li>Identify the quantities involved.</li>
                <li>Determine the operations needed to relate these quantities.</li>
                <li>Write a numerical expression that captures the relationships.</li>
                <li>Evaluate the expression to find the solution.</li>
            </ol>
        </p>    
        <exercise xml:id="exercise-write-and-evaluate-expressions">
            <title>Write and Evaluate Expressions</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Write a numerical expression for the following problem: "A store sells apples for $2 each and oranges for $3 each. If you buy 4 apples and 5 oranges, how much do you spend in total?"
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    The numerical expression is <m>4 \cdot 2 + 5 \cdot 3</m>, which evaluates to $23.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </subsection>
    
